article.description: Sheryl Swoopes and Tina Thompson hardly needed their teammates after halftime.
article.headline: Swoopes, Thompson score nearly all Comet points
article.linkText: Swoopes, Thompson help Comets beat Sting
article.story: CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Sheryl Swoopes and Tina Thompson made sure the Houston Comets' second game of the season was nothing like their first. Swoopes scored 29 points and Thompson added 19 to lead the Houston Comets to a 60-53 victory over Charlotte in the Sting's season-opener Friday night. The two combined for all but 12 of Houston's points as the Comets (1-1) bounced back from Thursday's 64-55 season-opening loss to San Antonio. "We got other people shots and they couldn't knock them down, so we decided we would go to what we call 'the home' is and that was where it was," Houston coach Van Chancellor said. "They made big-time plays." Swoopes, limited to eight points on 4-of-13 shooting Thursday, scored eight straight points in a run that gave Houston a 38-32 lead with 11:38 left. Thompson's 3-pointer with 8:33 remaining gave the Comets their largest lead, 47-36. Swoopes' fadeaway from the left baseline with 2:03 left ended the Sting's comeback hopes. "It's definitely good to come back and redeem yourselves after a tough loss," Swoopes said. "I didn't perform, and I knew I had to come out and be more mentally focused." Andea Stinson scored 13 points for the Sting, who shot 37 percent and were outrebounded 27-20 in losing their second straight opener. "I think it was just opening-night jitters," Stinson said. "It's something we can fix." The Sting never trailed in the first half and took their largest lead, 27-22, on Charlotte Smith-Taylor's 17-footer at the buzzer. The Comets countered by scoring the first six points of the second half and went on to beat the Sting for the 15th time in 19 meetings, as Swoopes narrowly missed her sixth career 30-point game. "What can I say, she's an Olympian, she's an All-Star and she showed it tonight," Sting coach Trudi Lacey. "She hit some tough shots." The Sting made their debut in orange and blue uniforms and played on a newly painted court to match the colors of the expansion Charlotte Bobcats. The Sting's colors had been teal and purple to match the Hornets, who moved to New Orleans in 2002. Bobcats and Sting owner Bob Johnson watched the game from a courtside seat. Charlotte played without last year's leading scorer, Allison Feaster, who returned Friday after finishing her season for a team in France. She is expected to play Saturday at Washington.
